F. Nietzsche talked about forgetting as positive act, an internal etiquette that acts the majordomo of the mind. One exception: never forgetting promises made.

"Mirabeau, who had no memory for insults and vile actions done him and was unable to forgive simply because heâ€”forgot."

Wolfe's Severian as Autarch in BoTNS as opposite (supposedly) slowly turning schizophrenic due to overaccumulation of memories, multiple persons coexisting in one mind, losing his self in multiple memories. Being unable to forget things you no longer need is somewhat an insomnia.

Peter Pan in the original books is the other end, forgetting friends, loved ones, dear enemies, stuck in a perpetual going nowhere. As Leibniz said consciousness is memory. But in reality the brain never fully forgets anything, it's analogous to "methylating" memories to turn off
